President Barack Obama has issued a proclamation declaring December 17th as Wright Brothers Day. The proclamation highlights the significance of the Wright brothers' achievement of the world's first powered flight on December 17, 1903, in Kitty Hawk, North Carolina. The proclamation emphasizes the importance of innovation and exploration in American history and encourages the next generation of inventors and entrepreneurs. It also mentions the advancements made in science, technology, engineering, and math education, as well as the efforts to support innovators and startups. The proclamation concludes by acknowledging the ongoing spirit of the Wright brothers in the aspirations of the American people to continue making groundbreaking discoveries and advancements. The proclamation is in line with a joint resolution passed by Congress in 1963, designating December 17th as Wright Brothers Day and requesting the President to issue an annual proclamation to observe the day with appropriate ceremonies and activities.